Class MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledBooleanCircuit

java.lang.Object
  edu.biu.scapi.circuits.garbledCircuit.AbstractGarbledBooleanCircuit
      edu.biu.scapi.circuits.garbledCircuit.MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledBooleanCircuit
All Implemented Interfaces:
GarbledBooleanCircuit, java.io.Serializable
public class MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledBooleanCircuit
extends AbstractGarbledBooleanCircuit
implements java.io.Serializable

Our code is designed as such that in its constructor StandardGarbledBooleanCircuit constructs StandardGarbledGates. Each StandardGarbledGate garbled itself by creating a garbled turth table. The garble dtruth table is created row by row. Thus, if we use AES128MultiKeyEncryption first we will garbled the first row , then the second row etc.. Each row will require two AES operations and two setKey operations--i.e. the key will be set to the garbled value for each row.

However, AES set key operations are expensive, and different rows of the truth tables use the same keys. Consider a 2 input gate. There are a total of four keys(a 0 and a 1 for each wire). Yet if we use StandardGarbledBooleanCircuit with AES128MultiKeyEncryption we will perform a total of 8 setKey operations. If we garbled the entire truth table together however, we would be able to minimize this to 4 operations.

In order to minimize the number of row operations, we have to couple the garbled gate and the encryption scheme. They can no longer be totally separate entities. This presents an issue however, since for reasons of allowing users to easily extend our code and add new encrypyion schemes, we want the encryption schemes to be totally separate from the GarbledGates. (See Garbling * Schemes by Mihir Bellare, Viet Tung Hoang, and Phillip Rogaway for their discussion on garbling schemes as an entity in their own right). Therefore, we create the specialized {code MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledBooleanCircuit and MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledGate to allow us to minimize the number of setKey operations while still in general decoupling garbling encryption schemes from the gates and circuits.

The only difference of this class from StandardGarbledBooleanCircuit is that it uses {@link MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledGate}s instead of StandardGarbledGates. All of the major differences that we discussed take place in MinimizeAESSetKeyGarbledGate.

Note that currently only the constructor and not the verify method minimizes AES set key calls

Constructs a garbled circuit using AES128MultiKeyEncryption while minimizing the number od setKey operations performed.

Parameters:
ungarbledCircuit - the circuit that we will garble
mes - The MultiKeyEncryptionScheme that will be used to garble and compute this circuit.
allInputWireValues - a map that is passed as a parameter. It should be blank when passed as a parameter and the constructor will add to it the 0 and 1 SecretKey values for each input Wire. The reason that this is passed as a parameter and not created here or stored as a field is because we need the constructing and only the constructing party(from hereon in Alice) to have access to this. The second party--i.e. the one that will compute on the circuit(from hereon in Bob) should not know which input wire value is 0 and which is 1 nor should Bob have access to both the 0 and 1 values. Rather, Bob is given access to only a single value for each input wire, and he does not know what this value encodes. Alice gives Bob the appropriate garbled values for her inputs, and Bob gets the value for his input from Alice via oblivious transfer. Thus, we have designed this class so that only Alice will have access to the map with both values of each input wire.

Note that there is one case in which Alice will give this map to Bob: In the case of a malicious adversary, Alice will construct multiple circuits and Bob will ask Alice to uncover some of them to verify them(using our verify method. The way that Alice uncovers these is by giving Bob access to the allInputWireValues map. Bob calls the verify method and passes this map as well as the agreed upon(ungarbled) circuit to the verify method to test that Alice constructed the circuit correctly.

See Secure Multiparty Computation for Privacy-Preserving Data Mining by Yehuda Lindell and Benny Pinkas Section 3 for an overview of Yao's protocol, and a more in depth explanation of all that is discussed here.

Throws:

TweakNotSetException
